history.content: I'd say 127 is most useful/important, with 126 being a very close second, then 170, then 188.

children.subject: Could you elaborate on what you mean by "Don't try taking 126 and 189 together, it'll make 189 far harder than it needs to be". I'm planning on doing this next semester, and was primarily taking 126 not because it helps with 189, but because I think it's interesting in general. Also wanted to take 189 next sem as I think taking it with Prof Sahai would be a huge learning experience. Thanks!

Try to take 126 and 127 before 189 (you can also take 126 first and then the 127 + 189 together, but this is suboptimal). Don't try taking 126 and 189 together, it'll make 189 far harder than it needs to be

I don't think it's worth taking 170 or 188 from the perspective of preparing for 189. This is not to say you shouldn't take these classes, they just offer little in the way of preparing for 189

You can definitely get away with taking none of them before 189 without too much difficulty, but 127 has the most overlap and is a lot like a slower-paced 189 overview. 126 can help with a stronger probability background in terms of experience working with probability, but you only need to know the probability from 70. 170 and 188 are definitely a lot less important, but have their own small benifits.

for *Shewchuck's version* 126 isn't needed or even all that useful IMO if you understood continuous probability reasonably well in cs70. 127 is relevant and helpful, but I think it makes more sense to take it concurrently than to take it beforehand.
